Note:
TASK - Cooperative task / coroutine abstraction built on top of the
work-stealing deque.

A Task represents a unit of cooperative work submitted to a scheduler.
Each task carries a function pointer (Process pointer), an opaque user
argument, a state machine, a cooperative cancellation flag, and a
shared completion state that callers can join.

State machine:
  NEW       -> task created, not yet scheduled
  READY     -> pushed onto a work-stealing deque
  RUNNING   -> a worker is executing the function
  WAITING   -> task voluntarily yielded; back on the ready deque
  COMPLETED -> function returned; result_value holds the return value

Task layout (88 bytes):
  offset 0:  id                (8 bytes) - monotonically assigned id
  offset 8:  state             (8 bytes) - one of TASK_STATE_*
  offset 16: fn_ptr            (8 bytes) - function pointer (Process)
  offset 24: arg_ptr           (8 bytes) - opaque argument
  offset 32: result_value      (8 bytes) - return value once COMPLETED
  offset 40: cancel_flag       (8 bytes) - 0 = live, 1 = cancellation requested
  offset 48: mutex_ptr         (8 bytes) - protects join condition
  offset 56: cv_ptr            (8 bytes) - signaled when state -> COMPLETED
  offset 64: scheduler_ptr     (8 bytes) - owning Scheduler or 0
  offset 72: priority          (8 bytes) - scheduling priority hint
  offset 80: parent_id         (8 bytes) - id of parent task (0 if root)

Scheduler layout (40 bytes):
  offset 0:  queue_ptr         (8 bytes) - work-stealing deque
  offset 8:  next_task_id      (8 bytes) - atomic id allocator
  offset 16: live_task_count   (8 bytes) - tracked outstanding tasks
  offset 24: mutex_ptr         (8 bytes) - protects counters
  offset 32: shutdown_flag     (8 bytes) - 1 = scheduler stopped

Dependencies:
- threading/sync_core.runa
- threading/thread_core.runa
- core/atomic_core.runa
- memory/layout.runa
- core/memory_core.runa
- concurrency/work_stealing_queue.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/thread_core.runa" as Thread
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Mem
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/concurrency/work_stealing_queue.runa" as WSQ

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Task layout constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TASK_OFF_ID as Integer is 0
Constant TASK_OFF_STATE as Integer is 8
Constant TASK_OFF_FN as Integer is 16
Constant TASK_OFF_ARG as Integer is 24
Constant TASK_OFF_RESULT as Integer is 32
Constant TASK_OFF_CANCEL as Integer is 40
Constant TASK_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 48
Constant TASK_OFF_CV as Integer is 56
Constant TASK_OFF_SCHED as Integer is 64
Constant TASK_OFF_PRIORITY as Integer is 72
Constant TASK_OFF_PARENT as Integer is 80
Constant TASK_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 88

Constant TASK_STATE_NEW as Integer is 0
Constant TASK_STATE_READY as Integer is 1
Constant TASK_STATE_RUNNING as Integer is 2
Constant TASK_STATE_WAITING as Integer is 3
Constant TASK_STATE_COMPLETED as Integer is 4

Constant TASK_OK as Integer is 1
Constant TASK_ERR_INVALID as Integer is 0
Constant TASK_ERR_CANCELLED as Integer is -1
Constant TASK_ERR_NOT_READY as Integer is -2
Constant TASK_ERR_FULL as Integer is -3
Constant TASK_ERR_SHUTDOWN as Integer is -4

Constant TASK_PRIORITY_LOW as Integer is 0
Constant TASK_PRIORITY_NORMAL as Integer is 1
Constant TASK_PRIORITY_HIGH as Integer is 2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scheduler layout constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant SCHED_OFF_QUEUE as Integer is 0
Constant SCHED_OFF_NEXT_ID as Integer is 8
Constant SCHED_OFF_LIVE as Integer is 16
Constant SCHED_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 24
Constant SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN as Integer is 32
Constant SCHED_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 40

Constant SCHED_DEFAULT_CAPACITY as Integer is 1024

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scheduler lifecycle
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
A scheduler owns the work-stealing deque, the id allocator and the live
task counter. A program typically uses a small number of schedulers
(commonly one per CPU). Tasks reference their scheduler so that yields
can re-queue work without callers passing it around.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate the 40-byte record, allocate the underlying WSQ with the given
capacity, allocate a guarding mutex for the counters and seed the id
allocator at 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Scheduler creation is O(1) plus a couple of primitive allocations. The
hot path through schedule/yield touches only the WSQ.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Schedulers are heap-owned. Callers must invoke scheduler_destroy when
no more tasks reference them.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scheduler_create" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cap be capacity
    If cap is less than or equal to 0:
        Set cap to SCHED_DEFAULT_CAPACITY
    End If
    Let s be proc allocate from Memory with SCHED_STRUCT_SIZE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let q be proc wsq_create from WSQ with cap
    If q is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with s
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc mutex_create from Sync
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc wsq_destroy from WSQ with q
        proc deallocate from Memory with s
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_QUEUE, q
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_NEXT_ID, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_LIVE, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX, mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 0
    Return s
End Process

Process called "scheduler_destroy" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let q be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_QUEUE
    If q is not equal to 0:
        proc wsq_destroy from WSQ with q
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    If mtx is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mtx
    End If
    proc deallocate from Memory with s
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_shutdown" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_is_shutdown" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN
End Process

Process called "scheduler_live_count" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let live be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_LIVE
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return live
End Process

@Reasoning
Atomically allocate a new task id. The scheduler keeps a monotonic
counter and increments it under the scheduler mutex so that creation
across multiple threads stays unique.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock the scheduler mutex, read the current counter, store counter+1
and return the previous value.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
A single mutex acquisition per task creation. For very high create
rates this can be replaced by an atomic_fetch_add primitive without
changing the public API.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal to the scheduler. The counter never wraps in practice (64-bit).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scheduler_allocate_id" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let id be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_NEXT_ID
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_NEXT_ID, (id plus 1)
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return id
End Process

Process called "scheduler_increment_live" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let live be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_LIVE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_LIVE, (live plus 1)
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_decrement_live" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let live be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_LIVE
    If live is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_LIVE, (live minus 1)
    End If
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Task lifecycle
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Create a NEW task bound to the given function pointer and argument. The
task starts in TASK_STATE_NEW until a call to task_submit places it on
the scheduler's queue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate 88 bytes, allocate a mutex and condvar for join synchronisation,
populate all fields and return the task pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Roughly the same cost as a future allocation: one heap allocation, one
mutex_create and one condvar_create.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The function pointer must remain valid for the lifetime of the task.
The argument pointer is owned by the caller; we do not retain it.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_create" takes scheduler as Integer, fn_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If scheduler is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If fn_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let t be proc allocate from Memory with TASK_STRUCT_SIZE
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc mutex_create from Sync
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with t
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cv be proc condvar_create from Sync
    If cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mtx
        proc deallocate from Memory with t
        Return 0
    End If
    Let id be proc scheduler_allocate_id with scheduler
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_ID, id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_NEW
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_FN, fn_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_ARG, arg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_RESULT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CANCEL, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX, mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CV, cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_SCHED, scheduler
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_PRIORITY, TASK_PRIORITY_NORMAL
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_PARENT, 0
    Return t
End Process

Process called "task_destroy" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CV
    If cv is not equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from Sync with cv
    End If
    If mtx is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mtx
    End If
    proc deallocate from Memory with t
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "task_id" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_ID
End Process

Process called "task_state" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_STATE_NEW
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let st be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return st
End Process

Process called "task_set_priority" takes t as Integer, priority as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let p be priority
    If p is less than TASK_PRIORITY_LOW:
        Set p to TASK_PRIORITY_LOW
    End If
    If p is greater than TASK_PRIORITY_HIGH:
        Set p to TASK_PRIORITY_HIGH
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_PRIORITY, p
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "task_get_priority" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_PRIORITY_NORMAL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_PRIORITY
End Process

Process called "task_set_parent" takes t as Integer, parent_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_PARENT, parent_id
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "task_parent_id" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_PARENT
End Process

Process called "task_argument" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_ARG
End Process

Process called "task_function" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_FN
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scheduling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Push a task onto the scheduler's deque so a worker may dispatch it. We
refuse submissions while the scheduler is shutting down so that
in-flight calls drain cleanly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Move the task to TASK_STATE_READY, increment the live counter, and call
wsq_push. If wsq_push reports FULL the task remains NEW and the caller
can retry or back off.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
A single wsq_push on the owner's deque is wait-free in the uncontended
case. The mutex used here only protects the small state machine.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The submitted task must outlive its execution; callers typically wait
on task_join before freeing it.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_submit" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_SCHED
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If proc scheduler_is_shutdown with s is equal to 1:
        Return TASK_ERR_SHUTDOWN
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let st be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE
    If st is not equal to TASK_STATE_NEW:
        If st is not equal to TASK_STATE_WAITING:
            proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
            Return TASK_ERR_NOT_READY
        End If
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_READY
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx

    Let q be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_QUEUE
    Let push_rc be proc wsq_push from WSQ with q, t
    If push_rc is less than 0:
        Note: Roll back state if the deque rejected us
        proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_NEW
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return TASK_ERR_FULL
    End If
    proc scheduler_increment_live with s
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "task_spawn" takes scheduler as Integer, fn_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc task_create with scheduler, fn_ptr, arg_ptr
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc be proc task_submit with t
    If rc is not equal to TASK_OK:
        proc task_destroy with t
        Return 0
    End If
    Return t
End Process

@Reasoning
Acquire the next ready task for the calling worker. A worker first tries
to pop from its owned deque (cache-friendly) and falls back to stealing.
This implementation operates on a single deque per scheduler; multi-deque
sharding is layered above this primitive.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Try wsq_pop_local first. If that returns 0, attempt wsq_steal. Return
the task pointer or 0 if the scheduler has nothing left to run.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Local pops are wait-free; steals incur a single CAS each.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Callers must not pop a task while it is still being submitted; the
internal state mutex serialises submit/transition.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scheduler_dequeue" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let q be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_QUEUE
    Let t be proc wsq_pop_local from WSQ with q
    If t is not equal to 0:
        Return t
    End If
    Set t to proc wsq_steal from WSQ with q
    Return t
End Process

@Reasoning
Mark a task as RUNNING so observers (cancel, join) can see progress.
The state mutex serialises this transition with task_cancel so that a
worker cannot start a task that has already been cancelled.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock the mutex, ensure state is READY (or WAITING after a yield), set
RUNNING and unlock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
A single mutex acquire per dispatch.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The worker calling this owns the task pointer until it transitions to
COMPLETED.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_begin_execution" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let cancelled be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CANCEL
    If cancelled is equal to 1:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return TASK_ERR_CANCELLED
    End If
    Let st be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE
    If st is not equal to TASK_STATE_READY:
        If st is not equal to TASK_STATE_WAITING:
            proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
            Return TASK_ERR_NOT_READY
        End If
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_RUNNING
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Cooperative yield: a running task voluntarily relinquishes the worker
and is pushed back onto the deque. Callers continue from where they left
off when re-dispatched by a worker.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Transition the state from RUNNING to WAITING, push the task back on the
scheduler's deque and request the OS to yield the current OS thread so
another worker can run.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Yield is rarely on the hot path; it costs a state transition, a deque
push and an OS yield.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Only the worker currently executing the task may call this.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_yield" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_SCHED
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let cancelled be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CANCEL
    If cancelled is equal to 1:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return TASK_ERR_CANCELLED
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_WAITING
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx

    Let q be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, SCHED_OFF_QUEUE
    Let push_rc be proc wsq_push from WSQ with q, t
    If push_rc is less than 0:
        Note: Deque is full; the worker must keep running this task
        proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_RUNNING
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return TASK_ERR_FULL
    End If
    proc thread_yield from Thread
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Complete a task with the given result value. This is the writer side of
the join: it stores the result, transitions the state to COMPLETED, and
wakes any thread blocked on task_join.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock the state mutex, store result, set state to COMPLETED, broadcast
the condvar (multiple joiners are permitted) and decrement the
scheduler's live counter.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex acquire + one condvar broadcast.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Called by the worker that executed the task.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_complete" takes t as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CV
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_RESULT, result
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_COMPLETED
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with cv
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_SCHED
    If s is not equal to 0:
        proc scheduler_decrement_live with s
    End If
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Signal cooperative cancellation. Tasks must observe the flag at safe
points (e.g. on entry to long-running loops) and exit promptly. Setting
the flag also wakes any waiter so they can re-check cancellation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Set the cancel flag under the state mutex and broadcast the condvar so
that joiners observe the change without spinning.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex acquire + broadcast.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Cancellation is advisory; tasks that ignore it cannot be forcefully
terminated by this layer.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_cancel" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CV
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CANCEL, 1
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with cv
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Process called "task_is_cancelled" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let c be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CANCEL
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return c
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Join
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Block the calling thread until the task transitions to COMPLETED, then
return its result. Cancelled tasks that finish still report their
result; tasks that never run will not unblock here, so callers must
ensure the scheduler is making progress.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Standard mutex+condvar wait loop: while state is not COMPLETED, call
condvar_wait. When it leaves the loop, read the result under the same
mutex and unlock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Joining a completed task is wait-free past the lock acquire. A pending
task pays the cost of a kernel-level wait.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The caller must not destroy the task before it transitions; multiple
threads can join the same task safely.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_join" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CV
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let st be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE
        If st is equal to TASK_STATE_COMPLETED:
            Let result be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_RESULT
            proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
            Return result
        End If
        proc condvar_wait from Sync with cv, mtx
    End While
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Bounded join with a microsecond timeout. Returns the result or
TASK_ERR_NOT_READY if the deadline elapses first.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Use condvar_timed_wait inside a loop. If the wait reports timeout (0)
and the task is still not COMPLETED, return without blocking further.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex acquire plus at most one kernel timed wait.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Same as task_join.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_try_join" takes t as Integer, timeout_us as Integer, out_result_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If out_result_holder is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_CV
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    Let st be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE
    If st is equal to TASK_STATE_COMPLETED:
        Let result be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_RESULT
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_result_holder, 0, result
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return TASK_OK
    End If
    proc condvar_timed_wait from Sync with cv, mtx, timeout_us
    Set st to proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_STATE
    If st is equal to TASK_STATE_COMPLETED:
        Let result2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_RESULT
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_result_holder, 0, result2
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return TASK_OK
    End If
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
    Return TASK_ERR_NOT_READY
End Process

@Reasoning
Indirect invocation helper. Allows a worker to dispatch a task without
knowing the concrete function type at the call site, mirroring the
indirect-call helpers used in future_promise.runa.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read the function pointer and argument from the task and call through
the standard 1-argument indirect-call shim. Callers that need
multi-argument shims should add specialised wrappers.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
A single indirect call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The function pointer must be a valid Process address. Cancellation is
checked before the dispatch.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "task_runtime_call_indirect_1" takes fn as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Indirect-call shim — real x86_64 indirect dispatch via inline asm.
    Note: fn at [rbp-8], a at [rbp-16], result at [rbp-24]. The function pointer
    Note: goes into rax, `a` becomes the System V first argument register rdi,
    Note: `call rax` performs the indirect branch, and the callee's return value
    Note: (already in rax) is stashed into result's stack slot for the Return
    Note: statement's epilogue.
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        .intel_syntax noprefix
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mov rdi, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        call rax
        mov qword ptr [rbp-24], rax
        .att_syntax prefix
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "task_dispatch" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TASK_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let rc be proc task_begin_execution with t
    If rc is not equal to TASK_OK:
        If rc is equal to TASK_ERR_CANCELLED:
            proc task_complete with t, 0
        End If
        Return rc
    End If
    Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_FN
    Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with t, TASK_OFF_ARG
    Let result be proc task_runtime_call_indirect_1 with fn, arg
    proc task_complete with t, result
    Return TASK_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Worker driver
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Workers loop until the scheduler shuts down and all tasks have drained.
This routine is what an OS-level worker thread runs once it has a
scheduler reference.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Loop: peek shutdown flag and live count. If shutdown is requested and
the deque is empty, exit. Otherwise attempt to dequeue and dispatch a
task. If the deque is empty, yield to give other workers a chance.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The loop is tight; OS yields when nothing is available avoid spinning.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Workers must not be re-entered after scheduler_destroy.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scheduler_run_once" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let t be proc scheduler_dequeue with s
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc task_dispatch with t
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "scheduler_run_until_empty" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let executed be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let did_work be proc scheduler_run_once with s
        If did_work is equal to 0:
            Return executed
        End If
        Set executed to executed plus 1
    End While
    Return executed
End Process
